        {
          "name": "Tornado",
          "version": [
            { "nr": "1", "release_date": "2010-07-23", "compatibility": [ "2.5-2.7" ] },
            { "nr": "2", "release_date": "2014-05-22", "compatibility": [ "2.5-2.7" ] },
            { "nr": "3", "release_date": "2013-03-29", "compatibility": [ "2.6-2.7" ] },
            { "nr": "4", "release_date": "2014-07-15", "compatibility": [ "2.6+", "3.2-3.9" ] },
            { "nr": "5", "release_date": "2018-03-05", "compatibility": [ "2.7+", "3.4-3.9" ] },
            { "nr": "6", "release_date": "2019-03-01", "compatibility": [ "3.5+" ] }
          ],
          "notes": "Confirmed working end-to-end via a real docker build+run on Python 3.12 (major 6, `tornado.web.Application` + `IOLoop.current().start()`). 0.x (2010-05-18) is a single ancient release, not independently version-bucketed (pre-PyPI-metadata era). Majors 1/2 (2010-2014) genuinely fail to even import on ANY Python 3.x -- confirmed via a real docker build: `tornado/web.py` uses Python-2-only tuple-parameter-unpacking lambda syntax (`lambda (l, s): ...`), a hard SyntaxError on Python 3 regardless of version. Majors 4/5 genuinely break starting Python 3.10 -- confirmed via a real docker build: `tornado/httputil.py` subclasses `collections.MutableMapping`, an alias Python removed from the `collections` module itself (moved to `collections.abc`) in 3.10; verified the exact boundary (works on 3.9, AttributeError on 3.10) for both majors directly, not assumed identical to major 6's floor. Only major 6 fixed this properly and has no upper bound."
        },
        {
          "name": "aiohttp",
          "version": [
            { "nr": "1", "release_date": "2016-09-16", "compatibility": [ "3.6" ] },
            { "nr": "2", "release_date": "2017-03-20", "compatibility": [ "3.6" ] },
            { "nr": "3", "release_date": "2018-02-12", "compatibility": [ "3.5+" ] }
          ],
          "notes": "Confirmed working end-to-end via a real docker build+run on Python 3.12 (major 3, `web.Application()` + `web.run_app()`). 0.x (2013-2016) predates asyncio's own stabilization in the stdlib and is not independently version-bucketed in this pass. A 4.0.0a1 alpha exists on PyPI but no stable 4.0 has shipped as of this writing -- not tracked. Majors 1/2's own PyPI classifiers claim 3.4-3.6 support, but 1.x genuinely fails to even import outside Python 3.6 exactly -- confirmed via a real docker build: `helpers.py` uses `asyncio.async` (an attribute name that became a SyntaxError once `async` was reserved as a keyword in Python 3.7), and separately fails on 3.5 too (verified) -- 3.6 is the only real working floor, not a range. Both majors 1 and 2 ALSO leave `async-timeout` (a transitive dependency) completely unversioned in their own setup.py -- pip resolves it to async-timeout's latest release (4.0.2), which itself needs a newer Python than these majors target, causing a real `TypeError: function() argument 1 must be code, not str` at import time (a stale/incompatible-bytecode symptom of the version mismatch) -- fixed with an explicit pin to async-timeout 3.0.1 (`FW_VERSION_EXTRA` in lang_python.py), the same class of unpinned-transitive-dependency bug already documented for Go's Iris/Echo and Node's several frameworks in this project."
        },
        {
          "name": "CherryPy",
          "version": [
            { "nr": "3",  "release_date": "2015-03-24", "compatibility": [ "2.7+", "3.1-3.7" ] },
            { "nr": "17", "release_date": "2018-07-13", "compatibility": [ "2.7+", "3.5+" ] },
            { "nr": "18", "release_date": "2018-09-01", "compatibility": [ "2.7+", "3.5+" ] }
          ],
          "notes": "Confirmed working end-to-end via a real docker build+run on Python 3.12 (major 18, `cherrypy.quickstart()` + `@cherrypy.expose`/`@cherrypy.tools.json_out()`). CherryPy released 16 numbered majors between 2015 and 2018 (3 through 18) -- confirmed via PyPI's real release history -- reflecting loose semver discipline in that era rather than 16 genuinely distinct API eras, the same pattern already documented for Node's Hapi package. Majors 4-16 are real, PyPI-installable releases but are NOT individually version-bucketed here (a disclosed density tradeoff, not a claim that they don't work); 3 and 17/18 were chosen as the long-lived-stable and current/final eras respectively. 18.x is CherryPy's last major (still receiving patches). Major 3 genuinely breaks starting Python 3.8 -- confirmed via a real docker build: `_cperror.py` does `from cgi import escape`, removed from the `cgi` module in Python 3.8 (deprecated since 3.2); verified the exact boundary directly (works on 3.7, ImportError on 3.8)."
        },
        {
          "name": "Bottle",
          "version": [
            { "nr": "0", "release_date": "2009-07-07", "compatibility": [ "2.5+", "3.0+" ] }
          ],
          "notes": "Bottle has never left the 0.x line in its entire history (0.4.3 through the current 0.13.x) -- confirmed via PyPI's full release list, the same single-major situation as this registry's own FastAPI entry. Confirmed working end-to-end via a real docker build+run on Python 3.12 (`@route('/')` + `run()`, single-file micro-framework by design)."
        },
        {
          "name": "Pyramid",
          "version": [
            { "nr": "1", "release_date": "2011-01-31", "compatibility": [ "2.6+", "3.2+" ] },
            { "nr": "2", "release_date": "2021-03-01", "compatibility": [ "3.6+" ] }
          ],
          "notes": "Confirmed working end-to-end via a real docker build+run on Python 3.12 (major 2, `Configurator()` + `add_route`/`add_view`, plain WSGI via `wsgiref.simple_server`). One real, found-the-hard-way fix: `pyramid.response.Response(text, content_type=...)` requires an explicit `charset` kwarg when the body is a text (not bytes) value -- omitting it throws `TypeError: You cannot set the body to a text value without a charset` at request time (a real docker-run failure, not a build-time error), confirmed by adding `charset=\"UTF-8\"`. `pcreate`/scaffolding is optional, not required, for this pattern -- no CLI scaffolding was needed."
        }
