            { "nr": "0.14", "release_date": "2025-02-25", "compatibility": [ "3.9+" ] },
            { "nr": "0.15", "release_date": "2026-05-06", "compatibility": [ "3.9+" ] }
          ],
          "notes": "The official Open Quantum Safe project's Python binding (github.com/open-quantum-safe/liboqs-python), a ctypes wrapper around the liboqs C library -- the Python equivalent of Go's liboqs-go / PHP's php-liboqs / .NET's LibOQS.NET / Node's liboqs-node, and the one language in this project that previously had NO liboqs binding tracked at all despite every other language having one. Requires the liboqs C library built from source in the same Dockerfile stage (git clone + cmake + ninja, the same recipe already used for the other languages' liboqs bindings) plus `LD_LIBRARY_PATH=/usr/local/lib` so the ctypes loader can find the resulting shared library at runtime -- no compilation of the Python package itself (it's pure ctypes, not a C extension). Confirmed working end-to-end via a real docker build+run: `import oqs; oqs.KeyEncapsulation('ML-KEM-768').generate_keypair()` returns a real 1184-byte ML-KEM-768 public key -- unlike Node's liboqs-node, this binding is built against a current liboqs release and exposes the final NIST algorithm names directly, no draft-name caveat needed."
        },
